Advisory Neighborhood Commission 5B strongly supports that DDOT design and implement the new Strategic Bikeways Plan as an update to the 2021 moveDC bicycle priority network;   ANC 5B supports the focus on filling neighborhood gaps between existing bike infrastructure, in order to increase network connectivity and safety for all road users outside of arterial corridors, given current planning and delivery capacity; ANC 5B supports including a focus on quick build and short
trip oriented improvements in the Strategic Bicycle Plan, such as adding contraflow lanes to 
10th St NE between Taylor St NE and Varnum St NE and in other locations; ANC 5B continues to support the implementation of the Taylor St protected bike lanes, which would serve as the first major east-west bicycle corridor, connecting Woodridge, Brookland, and North / Michigan Park to the Metropolitan Branch Trail (MBT) and serving as a safe crossing of the railroad tracks to the west of ANC 5B;

ANC 1A urges DCPS and the Office of the Deputy Mayor for Education to provide stabilized funding for Tubman ES in FY27, at no less than current school-based staffing levels, and to avoid further programmatic or personnel cuts driven by short-term, swing-space-related enrollment shocks; 

ANC 1A calls on DCPS and the DME to adjust enrollment projections for Tubman to reflect likely returning in-boundary families and to correct for disruptions created by the modernization and swing-space plan, rather than treating the swing year as a new baseline; and

ANC 1A supports and urges adoption of the Council’s “Holding School Budgets Harmless During Modernizations Amendment Act of 2025” (Bill B26-0072), which would prohibit reductions in a school’s budget when the school is or will be utilizing a swing space due to a modernization or other capital project, and urges DCPS, DME, the Mayor, and the Council to apply this hold-harmless principle in the FY27 budget for Tubman ES and other schools.

Advisory Neighborhood Commission 2C:

